\begin{document}
\begin{equation*}DDR={\Delta}V/DDT,\end{equation*}\end{document}

where ΔV = 20 mV, and we can similarly define DDRs, 
DDRf, and DDRc. Since the DDR is determined by the 
capacitative current (Icap = C
m dV
m/dt) and this capacitative current is equal to Iion + Ic, but of opposite sign, 
the DDR for each cell is affected by the coupling current. As we showed in Fig. 5, there is a net coupling current during diastole for two coupled cells, which is in 
the direction from the cell that had the higher intrinsic 
DDR to the cell that had the lower intrinsic DDR. Since 
the magnitude of the coupling current is the same for the 
two cells (just being opposite in sign), we proposed the 
hypothesis that the change in DDR that occurred with 
coupling would be predicted as:
